  <h3>1. Why Kenyan Businesses Get Keyword Research Wrong</h3>
  <p>From our audit data, here are the most common keyword mistakes specific to Kenyan websites:</p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mistake 1A: Targeting only high‑volume, generic keywords.</strong> A Nairobi plumber targeting “plumber” competes with national directories, home service aggregators, and 500+ other plumbers. But targeting “emergency plumber Kilimani 24 hours” has much lower competition.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 1B: Ignoring local modifiers.</strong> “SEO services” vs “SEO services Nairobi Kenya” – the latter is what voice users actually say.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 1C: Forgetting question keywords.</strong> Voice search is conversational. “How much does SEO cost in Kenya?” is a voice query; “SEO pricing” is a typed query. You need both.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 1D: No Swahili or Sheng keywords.</strong> Many Kenyans mix languages. “Duka la simu karibu nami” (phone shop near me) is a real voice search query that few websites target.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 1E: Keyword stuffing instead of natural integration.</strong> Repeating “best plumber Nairobi” 20 times on a page does not work – Google penalizes it.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 1F: No keyword mapping.</strong> Using the same keywords across multiple pages (cannibalization) confuses Google and prevents any page from ranking.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Fix these sub‑mistakes, and your rankings will improve – often within 30 days.</strong></p>

