  <h3>4. How to Check Keyword Competition (Free Method)</h3>
  <p>You do not need a paid tool to estimate competition. Use this free method:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Search for the exact keyword phrase in incognito mode on Google.</li>
    <li>Look at the top 3 results. Are they big brands, national directories (e.g., Yellow Pages, Jumia), or Wikipedia? If yes, competition is high – you may struggle to rank.</li>
    <li>If the top results are small local businesses, forums (Reddit, Quora), or blogs, competition is low to medium – you can likely outrank them with better content.</li>
    <li>Check if there is a “People also ask” box or featured snippet – those are opportunities to steal the snippet.</li>
    <li>Look at the word count and quality of the top results. If they are thin (under 500 words), you can beat them with a 1,200+ word comprehensive guide.</li>
  </ol>
  
  <p><strong>Target keywords where:</strong> Top results are not big brands, content is thin, and there is a featured snippet opportunity. These are your low‑hanging fruit.</p>

  <h3>5. Where to Place Keywords on Your Website (On‑Page Optimization)</h3>
  <p>Finding keywords is useless if you do not place them correctly. Prioritize these locations:</p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Page title (title tag):</strong> Most important. Include your primary keyword within the first 60 characters. Example: “Emergency Plumber Kilimani – 24/7 Service | Plumber Kenya”</li>
    <li><strong>Meta description:</strong> Not a ranking factor directly, but influences click‑through rate. Include the keyword naturally within 150‑160 characters.</li>
    <li><strong>H1 heading:</strong> Use exactly one H1 per page, and include your primary keyword. Example: “Affordable SEO Services in Nairobi – Get a Free Audit”</li>
    <li><strong>H2 and H3 subheadings:</strong> Use secondary and long‑tail keywords. Example: “How Much Does SEO Cost in Kenya? (2026 Pricing)”</li>
    <li><strong>First 100 words of content:</strong> Google gives more weight to early content. Start your page by answering the query directly, using your primary keyword.</li>
    <li><strong>Image alt text:</strong> Describe images using keywords naturally. Example: “plumber-fixing-leak-kilimani-nairobi.jpg” with alt text “Emergency plumber fixing a leaking pipe in Kilimani, Nairobi”.</li>
    <li><strong>URL slug:</strong> Keep URLs short and include the primary keyword. Example: /emergency-plumber-kilimani instead of /services/plumbing/emergency/kilimani-nairobi-24-7.</li>
    <li><strong>Internal anchor text:</strong> When linking to other pages on your site, use descriptive keyword‑rich anchor text (not “click here”).</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Do not:</strong> Keyword stuff. Use the keyword naturally, and also use synonyms and related terms (LSI keywords). Google’s algorithm understands context.</p>

