  <h3>1. Why Mobile Optimization Is Non‑Negotiable for Kenyan Websites</h3>
  <p>Consider these Kenya‑specific facts:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>89.3% mobile penetration</strong> – almost every internet user in Kenya uses a smartphone or feature phone to browse.</li>
    <li><strong>Google mobile‑first indexing</strong> – since 2019, Google uses the mobile version of your site for ranking. If your mobile site lacks content that your desktop site has, Google acts as if that content does not exist.</li>
    <li><strong>58.6% of voice searches happen on mobile</strong> – voice search is mobile search. If your mobile site is slow or broken, voice assistants will ignore you.</li>
    <li><strong>53% of users abandon a site that takes more than 3 seconds to load on mobile</strong> – and Kenyan 3G/4G speeds are often slower than global averages.</li>
    <li><strong>Mobile user experience affects local pack rankings</strong> – Google prioritizes mobile‑friendly businesses for “near me” queries.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <div style="background: #e8f5e9; padding: 20px; border-radius: 16px; margin: 25px 0;">
    <p><strong>📊 The Cost of Ignoring Mobile:</strong> A Nairobi e‑commerce store with a non‑responsive site lost an estimated 67% of mobile traffic. After fixing to responsive design, mobile conversions increased 340% within 60 days. The fix cost KES 15,000 – recovered in 4 days of additional sales.</p>
