  <h3>2. Common Mobile Optimization Mistakes (Kenyan Websites)</h3>
  <p>From our audit database, these are the most frequent mobile errors:</p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mistake 2A: No responsive design.</strong> The site looks fine on desktop but requires zooming and horizontal scrolling on mobile. This is the #1 mobile sin.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 2B: Tiny font sizes.</strong> Body text under 16px is unreadable on mobile without zooming. Google penalizes this.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 2C: Tap targets too small or too close.</strong> Buttons, links, and form fields need at least 48x48 pixels of touch area. Many Kenyan sites have 20x20 buttons – impossible to tap accurately.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 2D: Slow mobile load times.</strong> Uncompressed images, render‑blocking JavaScript, and poor hosting lead to 5+ second load times on 3G.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 2E: Popups and interstitials that are hard to close.</strong> Popups that cover content and have tiny “X” buttons frustrate mobile users and are penalized by Google.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 2F: Missing viewport meta tag.</strong> Without `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">`, mobile browsers assume a desktop width and scale down, making text tiny.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 2G: Blocked resources (CSS, JavaScript, images).</strong> If your robots.txt blocks Googlebot from accessing mobile CSS/JS, Google cannot render your mobile page properly.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Fix these sub‑mistakes in priority order – responsive design first, then speed, then tap targets.</strong></p>

  <h3>3. How to Test Your Website’s Mobile Friendliness (Free Tools)</h3>
  <p>Run these tests immediately. If you fail any, prioritize fixing.</p>
  
  <h4>3.1 Google Mobile‑Friendly Test</h4>
  <p>Go to <strong>search.google.com/test/mobile-friendly</strong>. Enter your URL. The tool shows: “Page is mobile‑friendly” (green) or “Page is not mobile‑friendly” (red) with specific issues listed. Run this on your homepage and top 5 landing pages.</p>
  
  <h4>3.2 Google PageSpeed Insights (Mobile)</h4>
  <p>Go to <strong>pagespeed.web.dev</strong>. Enter your URL. Select “Mobile” tab. It provides a score (0‑100) and specific optimization opportunities. Aim for 90+.</p>
  
  <h4>3.3 Chrome DevTools (Device Emulation)</h4>
  <p>Open Chrome, press F12, click the “Toggle device toolbar” icon (phone icon). Select a mobile device (e.g., iPhone 12 or Pixel 5). Resize your browser. Interact with your site. Does text become tiny? Do you have to scroll horizontally? Can you tap buttons easily?</p>
  
  <h4>3.4 Real Device Testing (Most Accurate)</h4>
  <p>Nothing beats testing on an actual smartphone. Open your site on a cheap Android phone (e.g., Tecno, Infinix, Samsung A series). Use 3G/4G (not Wi‑Fi). Navigate around. Does it frustrate you? If yes, your customers are also frustrated.</p>

  <h3>4. Responsive Design – The Correct Approach</h3>
  <p>There are two ways to make a site mobile‑friendly: <strong>responsive design</strong> (recommended) or <strong>separate mobile URL</strong> (e.g., m.yoursite.com – not recommended). Google prefers responsive design because:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Single URL for desktop and mobile – easier to share and link.</li>
    <li>No duplicate content issues.</li>
    <li>Faster to maintain – one set of pages.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>4.1 How to Implement Responsive Design (For Developers)</h4>
  <p>Add the viewport meta tag to every page’s `<head>`:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"&gt;
  </pre>
  <p>Use CSS media queries to adjust layouts at different screen widths. Example:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .container { padding: 10px; }
  .grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  h1 { font-size: 1.8rem; }
}
  </pre>
  
  <p><strong>For non‑developers:</strong> If you use a website builder (WordPress, Wix, Squarespace), most modern themes are responsive by default. However, check that you haven’t disabled responsive features or added fixed‑width elements.</p>

  <h3>5. Core Web Vitals – Google’s Mobile Performance Standard</h3>
  <p>Core Web Vitals are a set of metrics that measure real‑world user experience. Failing them hurts mobile rankings significantly. For Kenyan websites, the most common failures are:</p>
  
