  <h3>6. Step‑by‑Step Fixes for Mobile Optimization (Non‑Technical & Technical)</h3>
  
  <h4>Fix #1: Add Viewport Meta Tag (2 minutes)</h4>
  <p>Check your page’s `<head>` section. If you don’t see `<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">`, add it. This tells mobile browsers to set page width to device width.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #2: Increase Font Sizes (5 minutes)</h4>
  <p>Body text should be at least 16px. Headings should be proportionally larger. In your CSS, set:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
body { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; }
h1 { font-size: 1.8rem; }
h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; }
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  body { font-size: 16px; } /* already 16px, but ensure minimum */
}
  </pre>
  
  <h4>Fix #3: Enlarge Tap Targets (10 minutes)</h4>
  <p>Buttons, links, and form inputs need at least 48x48 pixels of touch area. Add CSS:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
button, .btn, a.button, input[type="submit"] {
  padding: 12px 24px;
  min-height: 48px;
  min-width: 48px;
}
  </pre>
  <p>Ensure links in paragraphs are spaced apart – add `margin` between them.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #4: Compress Images for Mobile (15 minutes)</h4>
  <p>Large images are the #1 cause of slow LCP. Use <strong>TinyPNG</strong> or <strong>Squoosh.app</strong> to compress images. Aim for under 200KB per image. Use `loading="lazy"` on images below the fold.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #5: Enable Browser Caching & CDN (30 minutes)</h4>
  <p>Browser caching stores static assets on the user’s phone for repeat visits. Use a caching plugin (if WordPress) or add `.htaccess` rules for Apache. For a CDN, <strong>Cloudflare</strong> offers a free plan with a Nairobi edge – sign up and change your nameservers. This alone can reduce mobile load time by 40%.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #6: Remove Render‑Blocking Resources (1 hour)</h4>
  <p>PageSpeed Insights will list “Eliminate render‑blocking resources”. Move non‑critical JavaScript to the bottom of the page or add `defer`/`async`. Inline critical CSS (as shown in Section 10 of voice search guide).</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #7: Test and Iterate</h4>
  <p>After each fix, re‑run PageSpeed Insights and the Mobile‑Friendly Test. Aim for incremental improvements.</p>

  <h3>7. Mobile UX for Kenyan Users – Thumb Zones, Click‑to‑Call, and M‑Pesa</h3>
  <p>Beyond technical fixes, consider how Kenyans actually use mobile:</p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Thumb zone optimization:</strong> Most users hold their phone with one hand and use their thumb. Place important CTAs (Call Now, WhatsApp, Directions) in the bottom half of the screen – the natural thumb reach.</li>
    <li><strong>Click‑to‑call links:</strong> Every phone number on your mobile site should be a `tel:` link. Example: `<a href="tel:+254710346425">Call us now</a>`. When tapped, it opens the dialer directly.</li>
    <li><strong>M‑Pesa integration:</strong> If you accept payments, offer M‑Pesa as an option prominently on mobile. Voice and mobile users expect M‑Pesa.</li>
    <li><strong>WhatsApp click‑to‑chat:</strong> Add a WhatsApp button that opens a chat with a pre‑filled message. Example: `<a href="https://wa.me/254710346425?text=Hello%2C%20I%20need%20help%20with%20mobile%20SEO">Chat on WhatsApp</a>`.</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid hover effects:</strong> Hover works on desktop, not on mobile. Use `:active` or `:focus` instead.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>These UX improvements directly increase conversion rates from mobile traffic – including voice‑driven visitors.</p>

