  <h3>2. Common Speed Mistakes (Kenyan Websites)</h3>
  <p>From our audit database, these are the most frequent speed errors:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mistake 3A: Unoptimized images.</strong> Using raw JPEGs from a camera (2-5MB each) instead of compressed WebP (100-200KB). Images account for 70% of page weight on most Kenyan sites.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 3B: No caching.</strong> Every visitor downloads the same CSS, JS, and images from scratch. Browser caching can reduce repeat load time by 80%.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 3C: Poor hosting (international server, shared).</strong> A US-based shared host adds 300-600ms latency to every request for Kenyan users.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 3D: Render‑blocking JavaScript and CSS.</strong> The browser loads these before showing anything, delaying first paint by seconds.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 3E: No CDN.</strong> Content Delivery Networks cache static assets on edge servers closer to users. Without a CDN, each request travels to the origin server.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 3F: Too many external scripts (ads, trackers, chat widgets).</strong> Each script adds network requests and JavaScript execution time.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 3G: Not using modern image formats.</strong> JPEG/PNG are larger than WebP or AVIF.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Fix these in order:</strong> Images → Hosting/CDN → Caching → Critical CSS → Remove render‑blocking resources.</p>

  <h3>3. How to Measure Your Site Speed (Free Tools)</h3>
  <p>You cannot fix what you do not measure. Run these tests and record the numbers.</p>
  
  <h4>3.1 Google PageSpeed Insights (Most Important)</h4>
  <p>Go to <strong>pagespeed.web.dev</strong>. Enter your URL, select “Mobile”. It gives:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A score from 0-100 (aim for 90+).</li>
    <li>Core Web Vitals: LCP, INP, CLS – pass/fail.</li>
    <li>Diagnostics: specific opportunities to improve (e.g., “Serve images in next‑gen formats”, “Eliminate render‑blocking resources”).</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>3.2 WebPageTest.org (Advanced)</h4>
  <p>Go to <strong>webpagetest.org</strong>. Choose “Mobile – 3G Slow” or “4G” and a test location close to Kenya (e.g., “Africa – South Africa” or “Europe – London”). It provides a waterfall chart showing exactly which resources load when. This is invaluable for debugging.</p>
  
  <h4>3.3 Chrome DevTools Lighthouse</h4>
  <p>Open Chrome, press F12 → Lighthouse tab → Generate report. It audits performance, accessibility, and SEO.</p>
  
  <h4>3.4 Real User Monitoring (RUM) via Google Analytics</h4>
  <p>In GA4, go to Reports → Tech → Web Vitals. This shows real LCP, INP, CLS from actual visitors (not synthetic tests). Most reliable.</p>

  <h3>4. Step‑by‑Step Speed Fixes (From Easy to Advanced)</h3>
  
  <h4>Fix #1: Compress and Convert Images (1 hour – huge impact)</h4>
  <p>Images are the #1 speed killer. Use these free tools:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Squoosh.app:</strong> Drag and drop images, convert to WebP, reduce quality to 80-85%. No visible difference, file size drops 50-70%.</li>
    <li><strong>TinyPNG / TinyJPG:</strong> Batch compress up to 20 images at once.</li>
    <li><strong>For bulk conversion (advanced):</strong> Use ImageMagick command line or a plugin like EWWW (WordPress).</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Target file sizes:</strong> Hero image under 200KB, product images under 100KB, icons under 20KB.</p>
  <p><strong>Serve WebP/AVIF:</strong> Use `<picture>` element with fallback:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;picture&gt;
  &lt;source srcset="image.avif" type="image/avif"&gt;
  &lt;source srcset="image.webp" type="image/webp"&gt;
  &lt;img src="image.jpg" alt="description" loading="lazy"&gt;
&lt;/picture&gt;
  </pre>
  
  <h4>Fix #2: Enable Browser Caching (15 minutes)</h4>
  <p>Add to your `.htaccess` file (Apache) or nginx config:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;IfModule mod_expires.c&gt;
  ExpiresActive On
  ExpiresByType image/jpeg "access plus 1 year"
  ExpiresByType image/webp "access plus 1 year"
  ExpiresByType text/css "access plus 1 month"
  ExpiresByType application/javascript "access plus 1 month"
&lt;/IfModule&gt;
  </pre>
  <p>For WordPress, use a caching plugin like <strong>LiteSpeed Cache</strong> or <strong>W3 Total Cache</strong>.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #3: Use a CDN (30 minutes – free)</h4>
  <p>A CDN stores copies of your site on servers around the world. For Kenyan users, a CDN with an African edge server dramatically reduces latency.</p>
  <p><strong>Cloudflare (free plan):</strong> Sign up, change your domain’s nameservers to Cloudflare’s. It includes a Nairobi edge location (since 2023). TTFB can drop from 400ms to 50ms for cached assets.</p>
  <p><strong>Other CDNs:</strong> BunnyCDN (pay as you go, has Johannesburg edge), or use your host’s built‑in CDN.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #4: Choose Kenya‑Friendly Hosting (Critical)</h4>
  <p>If your host’s servers are in the US or Europe, every request has a 200-500ms round trip before any content is sent. Options for better TTFB from Kenya:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Truehost Kenya:</strong> Local servers in Nairobi. TTFB 50-150ms. Affordable.</li>
    <li><strong>HostPoa:</strong> Kenyan hosting, good support.</li>
    <li><strong>Cloudflare CDN (free):</strong> Keep your existing host but route through Cloudflare – cached assets served from Nairobi edge.</li>
    <li><strong>Netlify / Vercel (static sites):</strong> Their global CDN includes African edges. Excellent for static HTML sites.</li>
    <li><strong>AWS Africa (Cape Town):</strong> Best for dynamic sites needing full control. Latency ~150ms from Nairobi.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>Fix #5: Enable Brotli Compression (Better than Gzip)</h4>
  <p>Brotli compresses text (HTML, CSS, JS) 20-30% smaller than Gzip. Most modern hosts support it. Test at <strong>https://www.brotli-tester.com/</strong>. If not enabled, ask your host to enable or add to .htaccess:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;IfModule mod_brotli.c&gt;
  AddOutputFilterByType BROTLI_COMPRESS text/html text/css text/javascript application/javascript text/plain
&lt;/IfModule&gt;
  </pre>
  
  <h4>Fix #6: Defer Render‑Blocking JavaScript</h4>
  <p>PageSpeed Insights will list “Eliminate render‑blocking resources”. For scripts not needed for above‑the‑fold content, add `defer` or `async`:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;script src="non-critical.js" defer&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;script src="analytics.js" async&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
  </pre>
  <p>`defer` loads after HTML parsing, in order. `async` loads and executes as soon as downloaded. Use `defer` for most scripts.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #7: Inline Critical CSS (Advanced – but powerful)</h4>
  <p>Extract CSS needed for above‑the‑fold content and put it directly in `<style>` tags. The rest loads asynchronously. Use tools like <strong>CriticalCSS.com</strong> or <strong>Penthouse</strong> to generate critical CSS. This can cut First Contentful Paint by 40-60%.</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #8: Lazy Load Everything Below the Fold</h4>
  <p>Add `loading="lazy"` to all images and iframes. For images in the viewport, use native lazy loading:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;img src="image.jpg" loading="lazy" alt="description"&gt;
&lt;iframe src="video.mp4" loading="lazy"&gt;&lt;/iframe&gt;
  </pre>
  
  <h4>Fix #9: Reduce Third‑Party Scripts</h4>
  <p>Each chat widget, analytics pixel, ad script, and tracking code adds network requests and JavaScript execution. Audit your site: Remove any script that is not essential. Use <strong>GTmetrix</strong> to see third‑party impact. Consider loading non‑critical scripts after page load (setTimeout).</p>
  
  <h4>Fix #10: Upgrade Hosting (If Everything Else Fails)</h4>
  <p>Cheap shared hosting is often overloaded. If your TTFB is consistently above 400ms after optimization, consider upgrading to a VPS or cloud hosting. <strong>Netlify (static) or Truehost VPS</strong> are good starts.</p>

  <h3>5. Core Web Vitals Deep Dive – What Each Metric Means & How to Fix</h3>
  
  <h4>5.1 LCP (Largest Contentful Paint) – Loading Speed</h4>
  <p><strong>Target:</strong> ≤ 2.5 seconds. <strong>Common causes of high LCP:</strong> Large hero images, slow server response, render‑blocking resources.</p>
  <p><strong>Fixes:</strong> Compress hero image (≤200KB), use a CDN, inline critical CSS, upgrade hosting, preload hero image: `<link rel="preload" href="hero.webp" as="image">`.</p>
  
  <h4>5.2 INP (Interaction to Next Paint) – Responsiveness</h4>
  <p><strong>Target:</strong> ≤ 200 milliseconds. <strong>Common causes:</strong> Long JavaScript tasks (heavy animations, inefficient code), too many third‑party scripts.</p>
  <p><strong>Fixes:</strong> Break up long tasks using `setTimeout`, defer non‑critical JS, remove unused JavaScript, use Web Workers for heavy processing.</p>
  
  <h4>5.3 CLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) – Visual Stability</h4>
  <p><strong>Target:</strong> ≤ 0.1. <strong>Common causes:</strong> Images without dimensions, fonts causing FOIT/FOUT, dynamically injected content (ads, popups).</p>
  <p><strong>Fixes:</strong> Always set `width` and `height` on images. Reserve space for ads. Use `font-display: optional` to reduce layout shift.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Track Core Web Vitals in Google Search Console:</strong> Go to “Core Web Vitals” report. It shows URLs with “Poor” or “Needs Improvement” status. Fix those pages first.</p>

