  <h3>1. Why Meta Tags Matter – More Than You Think</h3>
  <p>Many Kenyan business owners think meta tags are “old SEO” or irrelevant. This is dangerously wrong. Meta tags affect:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Click‑through rate (CTR):</strong> A compelling title and description can double your CTR, even if you rank in position 5. A poor one can halve it.</li>
    <li><strong>Keyword relevance:</strong> The title tag is a top‑3 ranking factor. Google gives significant weight to words in the title.</li>
    <li><strong>User experience:</strong> Users scanning search results decide within 2 seconds whether to click. Meta tags are their only information.</li>
    <li><strong>Voice search:</strong> Google Assistant often reads the title tag and meta description as part of the voice answer.</li>
    <li><strong>Social sharing:</strong> When your page is shared on social media, the title and description are pulled as the preview.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <div style="background: #e8f5e9; padding: 20px; border-radius: 16px; margin: 25px 0;">
    <p><strong>📊 The Cost of Bad Meta Tags:</strong> A Nairobi e‑commerce store had duplicate titles on 45 product pages. After fixing each title to be unique and compelling, CTR from search increased 67% within 30 days – without changing rankings. That is thousands of extra clicks for free.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>2. Common Meta Tag Mistakes (Kenyan Websites)</h3>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4A: Missing title tags.</strong> Some pages have no `<title>` tag at all. Google uses the URL as the title – which looks terrible in results.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4B: Duplicate title tags across multiple pages.</strong> Every page of your site should have a unique title. Common on e‑commerce sites: “Product Page – My Store” for 100 different products.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4C: Missing meta descriptions.</strong> Google then auto‑generates a snippet from the page content – often nonsensical.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4D: Titles too long (&gt;60 characters) or too short (&lt;30 characters).</strong> Google truncates long titles. Short titles miss keyword opportunities.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4E: Meta descriptions too long (&gt;160 characters) or too short (&lt;50 characters).</strong> Truncated descriptions lose message; short ones lack persuasive power.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4F: Keyword stuffing.</strong> “Plumber Nairobi, best plumber Nairobi, affordable plumber Nairobi” – looks spammy and can be penalized.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4G: No call to action.</strong> “Learn more”, “Shop now”, “Get a quote” – telling users what to do next improves CTR.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 4H: Duplicate content without canonical tags.</strong> Same content available at multiple URLs (e.g., http:// and https://, with and without www) – Google splits link equity.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Fix these in order:</strong> Ensure every page has a unique title and meta description → Optimize length and content → Implement canonical tags.</p>

