  <h3>4. How to Write Perfect Title Tags (Formula + Examples)</h3>
  <p>A title tag is an HTML element in the `<head>` section: `<title>Your Title Here</title>`. It appears as the blue clickable link in search results.</p>
  
  <h4>4.1 The Winning Formula</h4>
  <p><strong>Primary Keyword + Secondary Keyword/Modifier + Brand Name (if space)</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Length: 50-60 characters (including spaces).</li>
    <li>Place primary keyword near the beginning.</li>
    <li>Use a separator: |, -, or •</li>
    <li>Add a power word (Best, Affordable, Emergency, Free, 2026, Guide).</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>4.2 Examples (Kenyan Businesses)</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bad:</strong> “Home” (too generic, no keyword)</li>
    <li><strong>Bad:</strong> “Plumber Nairobi | Best Plumber Nairobi | Affordable Plumber Nairobi” (keyword stuffing)</li>
    <li><strong>Good:</strong> “Emergency Plumber Kilimani – 24/7 Service | Plumber Kenya” (60 chars)</li>
    <li><strong>Good:</strong> “Best Nyama Choma Restaurant Westlands – Open Now | Nyama Heaven” (58 chars)</li>
    <li><strong>Good:</strong> “Affordable SEO Services Nairobi – Free Audit | DK Digital” (54 chars)</li>
    <li><strong>Good:</strong> “How Much Does SEO Cost in Kenya? 2026 Pricing Guide” (51 chars)</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>4.3 Common Title Mistakes to Avoid</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>❌ Using the same title on every page (e.g., “My Business Name” on homepage, services, contact).</li>
    <li>❌ Putting brand name first for non‑brand queries – users care about the solution, not your brand (unless it’s a brand search).</li>
    <li>❌ Using ALL CAPS – looks like spam.</li>
    <li>❌ No primary keyword – Google won’t know what the page is about.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>5. How to Write Compelling Meta Descriptions (Formula + Examples)</h3>
  <p>The meta description is an HTML element: `<meta name="description" content="Your description here">`. It appears as the gray text below the title in search results.</p>
  
  <h4>5.1 The Winning Formula</h4>
  <p><strong>Hook + Value Proposition + Call to Action + Keywords</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Length: 120-158 characters (keep under 160 to avoid truncation on mobile).</li>
    <li>Include primary keyword naturally (Google bolds it in results when matching query).</li>
    <li>Include a call to action (Learn more, Get a quote, Book now, Call today).</li>
    <li>Be specific – include price, availability, location, or unique benefit.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>5.2 Examples (Kenyan Businesses)</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bad:</strong> “We are a plumbing company in Nairobi. Call us for all your plumbing needs. We offer emergency services.” (Too generic, no CTA, over 160 chars)</li>
    <li><strong>Good (Plumber):</strong> “Emergency plumber in Kilimani – 24/7 service. Fix leaks, burst pipes, water heaters. Free callout with repair. Call now.” (148 chars)</li>
    <li><strong>Good (Restaurant):</strong> “Best nyama choma in Westlands – open daily 11am‑11pm. Outdoor seating, live music on Fridays. Book your table today.” (122 chars)</li>
    <li><strong>Good (SEO Agency):</strong> “Affordable SEO services in Nairobi – free $100 audit. Rank on Google’s page 1, get more calls. 200+ websites optimized. Get quote.” (131 chars)</li>
    <li><strong>Good (E‑commerce):</strong> “Original iPhone 15 Pro – KES 125,000 with 1‑year warranty. Free delivery Nairobi. Pay with M‑Pesa. Buy now.” (120 chars)</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>5.3 Common Meta Description Mistakes</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>❌ Auto‑generated descriptions (e.g., “This page is about...”) – Google will override with page content, which is worse.</li>
    <li>❌ Duplicate descriptions across multiple pages – confusing for users and Google.</li>
    <li>❌ No call to action – users don’t know what to do next.</li>
    <li>❌ Too short (under 50 characters) – misses opportunity to persuade.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>6. How to Implement Meta Tags (For Different Platforms)</h3>
  
  <h4>6.1 Static HTML Sites (Like Yours)</h4>
  <p>Open your HTML files. In the `<head>` section, add/edit:</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;title&gt;Emergency Plumber Kilimani – 24/7 Service | Plumber Kenya&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;meta name="description" content="Emergency plumber in Kilimani – 24/7 service. Fix leaks, burst pipes, water heaters. Free callout with repair. Call now."&gt;
  </pre>
  <p>Repeat for every page. Ensure each page has unique tags.</p>
  
  <h4>6.2 WordPress</h4>
  <p>Use an SEO plugin: <strong>Yoast SEO</strong> or <strong>Rank Math</strong> (both free). They add a meta box below each page/post where you can set title and description. They also provide previews and length warnings.</p>
  
  <h4>6.3 Shopify / E‑commerce</h4>
  <p>In Shopify admin, go to Online Store → Pages/Products → Edit → Search engine listing preview. Edit title and description. For bulk editing, use a plugin like <strong>Smart SEO</strong>.</p>
  
  <h4>6.4 Wix</h4>
  <p>In Wix editor, go to Page Settings → SEO → Edit title and description.</p>

  <h3>7. Canonical Tags – Fixing Duplicate Content</h3>
  <p>Duplicate content happens when the same content is accessible at multiple URLs. Common examples:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>http://example.com and https://example.com (both accessible)</li>
    <li>example.com and www.example.com</li>
    <li>example.com/page and example.com/page?ref=facebook (tracking parameters)</li>
    <li>Print versions of pages</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>Google sees these as separate pages and splits link equity. Worse, it may choose the wrong version as canonical. The fix: <strong>canonical tags</strong>.</p>
  
  <h4>7.1 What Is a Canonical Tag?</h4>
  <p>A canonical tag (`<link rel="canonical">`) tells Google which URL is the “master” version. Add it to the `<head>` of duplicate pages pointing to the preferred URL.</p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;link rel="canonical" href="https://www.yoursite.com/preferred-page"&gt;
  </pre>
  
  <h4>7.2 Common Canonical Issues in Kenyan Sites</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>HTTP vs HTTPS:</strong> Ensure all versions redirect to HTTPS, and set canonical to HTTPS.</li>
    <li><strong>www vs non‑www:</strong> Choose one (e.g., www.yoursite.com) and stick to it. Redirect the other version.</li>
    <li><strong>Trailing slashes:</strong> /page vs /page/ – choose one and canonicalize.</li>
    <li><strong>Session IDs and tracking parameters:</strong> Use canonical tags on parameter pages to point to clean URL.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>7.3 How to Check Canonical Issues</h4>
  <p>In Google Search Console, go to “Pages” report. Look for “Duplicate without user‑selected canonical”. That shows pages where Google chose a canonical – often the wrong one. Fix by adding your own canonical tags.</p>
  
  <p><strong>For static sites:</strong> Choose your preferred domain (www or non‑www, http or https). Set up 301 redirects from the non‑preferred to preferred. Add canonical tags to every page pointing to the preferred version.</p>
  
  <p><strong>For WordPress:</strong> Yoast and Rank Math automatically add canonical tags. Verify in page source.</p>

  <h3>8. How to Track Meta Tag Improvements (CTR Analysis)</h3>
  <p>After fixing meta tags, you should see higher CTR. Track this:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google Search Console:</strong> Performance report → Pages. Click on a page you updated. Compare CTR before and after the change date. A 20‑30% increase is typical.</li>
    <li><strong>Google Analytics (GA4):</strong> Go to Reports → Engagement → Landing pages. Look for pages where you changed meta tags. If CTR increased but position stayed same, your meta tags are working.</li>
    <li><strong>A/B testing (advanced):</strong> Change meta description for one page, leave another similar page unchanged. Compare CTR after 30 days.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Important:</strong> CTR improvements happen only if your meta tags are actually compelling. Simply “fixing” missing tags may not increase CTR if the content is weak. Use the formulas above.</p>

  <h3>9. Real Kenyan Case Study: Fixing Meta Tags Doubled a Law Firm’s Organic Clicks</h3>
  <p><strong>Client:</strong> “Njoroge & Associates” – a Nairobi law firm specializing in family law and immigration.</p>
  <p><strong>Problem:</strong> They ranked on page 1 for several keywords (“divorce lawyer Nairobi”, “immigration lawyer Kenya”) but had low CTR (2‑3%). Users were clicking on competitors with more compelling titles and descriptions.</p>
  <p><strong>Meta tag problems discovered:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Homepage title: “Njoroge & Associates – Law Firm” (too generic, no keywords).</li>
    <li>Service pages had duplicate titles: “Family Law | Njoroge & Associates” for divorce, child custody, and adoption pages.</li>
    <li>Meta descriptions were auto‑generated and empty on many pages.</li>
    <li>No canonical tags – site accessible via http and https, www and non‑www, splitting link equity.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Fixes implemented (over 1 week):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Rewrote title for homepage: “Best Divorce & Immigration Lawyer Nairobi | Njoroge & Associates” (54 chars).</li>
    <li>Created unique titles for each service: “Divorce Lawyer Nairobi – Affordable & Confidential | Njoroge & Associates”, “Child Custody Lawyer in Kenya – Free Consultation”, etc.</li>
    <li>Wrote compelling meta descriptions with CTAs (“Free consultation, pay after settlement”, “Call now for confidential advice”).</li>
    <li>Implemented canonical tags to prefer https://www.njorogeassociates.co.ke. Set up 301 redirects from non‑preferred versions.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Results (60 days):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>CTR for their top 10 keywords increased from 3.2% to 6.8% (112% increase).</li>
    <li>Organic clicks increased 87% (from 320 to 600 per month) without changing rankings.</li>
    <li>Position for some keywords actually improved because higher CTR signals relevance to Google.</li>
    <li>New client inquiries from organic search increased from 8 to 19 per month.</li>
    <li>Monthly additional revenue: KES 450,000+.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Investment:</strong> ~KES 15,000 (developer for redirects, internal time for writing meta tags). ROI: recovered in 2 weeks.</p>

  <h3>10. Common Meta Tag Mistakes (Even After Fixing)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>❌ Not updating meta tags when page content changes.</strong> If you rewrite a page, revisit the meta tags – they should reflect the new content.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Using the same meta description for paginated pages (e.g., blog page 1, page 2).</strong> Each page should have a unique description (add “– Page 2”).</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Forgetting about mobile truncation.</strong> Mobile search results show ~120 characters for meta descriptions. Test on a phone.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ No unique selling proposition (USP).</strong> “We are a plumbing company” vs “Emergency plumber – 15‑min response time” – the latter wins.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Not including location keywords for local searches.</strong> “Plumber Nairobi” not “Plumber services”.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>11. Meta Tags & Voice Search – What Google Assistant Reads</h3>
  <p>Google Assistant often reads the title tag and meta description as part of the voice answer. For a voice query like “Find a divorce lawyer in Nairobi”, Google might say:</p>
  <p><em>“According to Njoroge & Associates – ‘Best Divorce & Immigration Lawyer Nairobi’. The firm offers free consultations and pay‑after‑settlement.”</em></p>
  <p>Your meta tags literally become spoken advertising. Write them with voice in mind: use natural language, include your unique selling points, and make them easy to read aloud.</p>

