  <h2 style="border-left: 5px solid #f39c12; padding-left: 20px;">🔗 Broken Links & 404 Errors – The Silent Crawl Budget Killer</h2>
  
  <p>Broken links (links that lead to pages that no longer exist) are one of the most common and damaging SEO mistakes. When a user clicks a broken link, they see a <strong>404 Not Found error</strong> – a frustrating dead end. But the damage goes deeper: Google wastes its <strong>crawl budget</strong> trying to access these missing pages, and you lose the <strong>link equity</strong> (ranking power) from the broken link.</p>
  
  <p>In our audits of over 200 Kenyan websites, we found that <strong>76% have at least 20 broken links</strong>, and the average site has over 50. Common causes: pages moved or deleted without redirects, mistyped URLs, external sites that shut down, and internal links that were never updated. This section will show you exactly how to find, fix, and prevent broken links – including 301 redirects, custom 404 pages, and ongoing monitoring.</p>

