  <h3>1. Why Broken Links Are a Critical SEO Mistake</h3>
  <p>Many Kenyan business owners think broken links are just a minor annoyance. They are wrong. Broken links harm SEO in three major ways:</p>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Wasted crawl budget:</strong> Google has limited time to crawl your site. Every 404 page it encounters is wasted time. Instead of discovering your new content, Googlebot is spinning its wheels on dead pages.</li>
    <li><strong>Lost link equity (PageRank):</strong> When you have a link from another site (backlink) or an internal link pointing to a broken page, that ranking power evaporates. You are throwing away authority.</li>
    <li><strong>Poor user experience (UX):</strong> Users who click a broken link will bounce back to search results and likely click a competitor. High bounce rates on 404s signal to Google that your site is poorly maintained.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduced trust & credibility:</strong> A site full of broken links looks abandoned. New visitors will question whether your business is still operating.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <div style="background: #e8f5e9; padding: 20px; border-radius: 16px; margin: 25px 0;">
    <p><strong>📊 The Cost of Broken Links:</strong> A Nairobi e‑commerce store had 147 broken internal links and 234 broken external links. After fixing them, Google crawled 40% more pages per month, and their rankings for 15 keywords improved by an average of 6 positions – without any other changes.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>2. Types of Broken Links (With Kenyan Examples)</h3>
  <p>There are three main types of broken links. Each requires a different fix.</p>
  
  <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 20px 0; background: #f8fafc; border-radius: 16px; overflow: hidden;">
    <thead style="background: #0a3d62; color: white;">
      <tr><th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Type</th><th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Example</th><th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Cause</th><th style="padding: 12px; text-align: left;">Fix</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;"><td style="padding: 12px;"><strong>Internal broken links</strong></td><td style="padding: 12px;">Linking to `/services/plumbing` but page moved to `/plumbing-nairobi`</td><td style="padding: 12px;">Page moved/deleted, typo in URL</td><td style="padding: 12px;">Update link URL or add 301 redirect</td></tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;"><td style="padding: 12px;"><strong>External broken links</strong></td><td style="padding: 12px;">Linking to a blog post on another site that was deleted</td><td style="padding: 12px;">External site removed page, changed URL</td><td style="padding: 12px;">Find new source or remove link</td></tr>
      <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;"><td style="padding: 12px;"><strong>Inbound broken links (backlinks)</strong></td><td style="padding: 12px;">Another site links to your old page `/about-us` but you moved to `/about`</td><td style="padding: 12px;">You changed URL without redirect</td><td style="padding: 12px;">Add 301 redirect from old to new URL</td></tr>
