  <h3>3. How to Find Broken Links (Free & Low-Cost Tools)</h3>
  
  <h4>3.1 Google Search Console (Free – Most Important)</h4>
  <p>GSC → “Pages” report → Look for “404” under “Not found (404)” in the “Reason” column. This shows you exactly which URLs on your site return 404 errors. These are pages that Google tried to crawl but couldn’t find. Click into each to see which pages link to the broken URL (internal or external).</p>
  <p><strong>Action:</strong> For each 404, decide: create a redirect (301) to a relevant page, or restore the page if it should exist.</p>
  
  <h4>3.2 Screaming Frog SEO Spider (Free up to 500 URLs)</h4>
  <p>Download Screaming Frog. Crawl your site. Go to the “Response Codes” tab. Filter by “Client Error (4xx)”. Screaming Frog lists every broken link on your site, including the source page (where the link lives) and the broken target URL.</p>
  
  <h4>3.3 Ahrefs Webmaster Tools (Free – for external broken links)</h4>
  <p>Ahrefs offers a free account that includes a site audit. It will crawl your site and report broken links (internal and external). It also shows which external sites have broken backlinks pointing to your site (so you can contact them to update the link).</p>
  
  <h4>3.4 Dr. Link Check (Free web tool)</h4>
  <p>Enter your URL, and Dr. Link Check scans your entire site for broken links. Simple and free, but limited to smaller sites (under 1,000 pages).</p>
  
  <h4>3.5 Manual Check (For small sites)</h4>
  <p>Click through your main navigation, footer links, and key content pages. Does every link go to a live page? If you find a 404, note the source page.</p>

  <h3>4. How to Fix Broken Internal Links (Step by Step)</h3>
  
  <h4>4.1 Update the Link URL (Easiest Fix)</h4>
  <p>If a page moved to a new URL and you know the new URL, simply update the link in your HTML or content editor. Example:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Old broken link: `<a href="/services/plumbing">Plumbing services</a>` (returns 404)</li>
    <li>New working URL: `/plumbing-services-nairobi`</li>
    <li>Fix: Change the `href` to the new URL.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>4.2 Add a 301 Redirect (Preserves Link Equity)</h4>
  <p>If you have many links pointing to the old URL (from internal pages or external backlinks), a 301 redirect is better. It tells Google that the page has permanently moved, and passes most of the ranking power.</p>
  <p><strong>For Apache (.htaccess):</strong></p>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
Redirect 301 /services/plumbing /plumbing-services-nairobi
  </pre>
  <p><strong>For WordPress:</strong> Use a plugin like <strong>Redirection</strong> or <strong>Rank Math</strong> (free). Go to Tools → Redirection → Add new source URL and target URL.</p>
  <p><strong>For static HTML sites:</strong> Use your server’s redirect rules (.htaccess for Apache, nginx config, or Netlify redirects file).</p>
  
  <h4>4.3 Remove the Link (If Page No Longer Exists and No Good Redirect Target)</h4>
  <p>If the content is gone and you have no similar page to redirect to, simply remove the broken link from your site. This is better than leaving a 404.</p>

  <h3>5. How to Fix Broken External Links (Links to Other Sites)</h3>
  <p>External broken links don’t directly hurt your site’s ranking, but they harm user experience and waste crawl budget (Googlebot follows them). Fixes:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Find an alternative source:</strong> If a resource page you linked to is gone, search for a similar article or resource on another reputable site.</li>
    <li><strong>Remove the link:</strong> If no good alternative exists, simply delete the link (keep the text, but remove the `<a>` tag).</li>
    <li><strong>Use archive.org:</strong> If the content was valuable but the site is permanently down, you can link to an archived version (but this is rare).</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Tool for finding external broken links:</strong> Ahrefs Webmaster Tools (free) → Site Audit → External links → Broken links.</p>

  <h3>6. How to Fix Inbound Broken Backlinks (Links From Other Sites to Your 404s)</h3>
  <p>This is the most valuable type of broken link to fix because you are losing link equity from other sites. When another website links to a page on your site that returns a 404, you lose that ranking power.</p>
  
  <h4>6.1 Find Inbound Broken Backlinks (Free)</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google Search Console:</strong> “Links” report → “Top linking sites” → Click on a site → See which of your pages they link to. Check if that page is a 404.</li>
    <li><strong>Ahrefs Webmaster Tools (free):</strong> Dashboard → “Broken backlinks” report. Shows all external sites linking to your 404 pages.</li>
    <li><strong>SEMrush (free limited):</strong> Backlink audit tool.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>6.2 Fixes for Inbound Broken Backlinks</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Best fix: Add a 301 redirect from the old 404 URL to a relevant live page.</strong> This preserves most of the link equity. Example: old page `/promo-2024` (404) redirect to `/current-offers`.</li>
    <li><strong>Second best: Restore the original page</strong> if the content is still valuable.</li>
    <li><strong>Contact the linking site:</strong> Ask them to update the link to your new URL. This works best if the site is a partner or directory.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>7. Custom 404 Page – Turn Errors into Opportunities</h3>
  <p>Even with perfect maintenance, some 404 errors will happen (users mistype URLs, old bookmarks). A <strong>custom 404 page</strong> keeps users on your site and can even convert them.</p>
  
  <h4>7.1 What a Good Custom 404 Page Includes</h4>
  <ul>
    <li>A clear message: “Page not found” (don’t just show browser error).</li>
    <li>Apologetic/friendly tone: “Oops! We couldn’t find that page.”</li>
    <li>Search bar: Let users search your site.</li>
    <li>Links to popular pages: Homepage, Services, Blog, Contact.</li>
    <li>Contact information: Phone number, WhatsApp, email – users may still want to reach you.</li>
    <li>Branding and navigation: Keep your header and footer so users can navigate away.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>7.2 Example Custom 404 Page HTML (Simple)</h4>
  <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #e2e8f0; padding: 15px; border-radius: 12px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.8rem;">
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;&lt;title&gt;Page Not Found – Your Business Name&lt;/title&gt;&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;404 – Page Not Found&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Sorry, we couldn't find the page you were looking for. It might have been moved or deleted.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Try our homepage: &lt;a href="/"&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Or contact us directly: &lt;a href="tel:+254710346425"&gt;Call us&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href="https://wa.me/254710346425"&gt;WhatsApp&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;form action="/search" method="get"&gt;
    &lt;input type="search" name="q" placeholder="Search our site..."&gt;
    &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Search&lt;/button&gt;
  &lt;/form&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
  </pre>
  
  <p><strong>WordPress:</strong> Many themes have a built‑in 404.php template. Edit it in Appearance → Theme Editor.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Static sites:</strong> Configure your server to use a custom 404.html page. On Apache: `ErrorDocument 404 /404.html` in .htaccess.</p>

  <h3>8. How to Prevent Broken Links (Ongoing Maintenance)</h3>
  <p>Prevention is better than cure. Implement these practices:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use relative paths for internal links carefully.</strong> If you move pages, relative paths can break. Consider using absolute paths (starting with /) for navigation.</li>
    <li><strong>When deleting a page, always add a 301 redirect</strong> to the most relevant live page (or to the homepage if no other page exists).</li>
    <li><strong>Use a link checker monthly.</strong> Schedule 30 minutes at the end of each month to run Screaming Frog or Ahrefs scan.</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid linking to external sites without checking stability.</strong> For important external resources, consider linking to archive.org or use a “link validator” plugin (WordPress).</li>
    <li><strong>Use a plugin that alerts you to broken links.</strong> For WordPress, <strong>Broken Link Checker</strong> (free) monitors links and emails you when a link breaks.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>9. How to Track Broken Link Fixes (Measure Impact)</h3>
  <p>After fixing broken links and adding redirects, track the impact:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google Search Console:</strong> The “Pages” report will show decreasing 404 errors over time. Aim for zero 404s on your internal pages (external 404s are less critical).</li>
    <li><strong>Crawl stats:</strong> In GSC → Settings → Crawl stats. After fixing broken links, you may see more pages crawled per day (because Googlebot isn’t wasting time on 404s).</li>
    <li><strong>Rankings & traffic:</strong> Monitor your top keywords. Fixing broken backlinks (inbound) often improves rankings for related keywords within 4‑8 weeks.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>10. Real Kenyan Case Study: Fixing Broken Links Recovered 80% of Lost Traffic</h3>
  <p><strong>Client:</strong> “Kenya Travel Hub” – a travel blog and tour booking site with 500+ blog posts and pages.</p>
  <p><strong>Problem:</strong> A site migration 6 months earlier changed many URL structures (from `/blog/post-name` to `/post-name`). The developer forgot to add 301 redirects. As a result, thousands of links (internal and external) pointed to 404 pages. Organic traffic had dropped 70% over 6 months, and the business didn’t know why.</p>
  <p><strong>Broken link audit findings:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>1,847 internal broken links (from pages linking to the old URL structure).</li>
    <li>342 inbound broken backlinks from external sites (travel directories, other blogs, social media).</li>
    <li>Google Search Console showed 2,300+ “404 not found” URLs.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Fixes implemented (over 3 weeks):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Created a bulk 301 redirect map: old URLs → new URLs using a regular expression rule in .htaccess: `RedirectMatch 301 ^/blog/(.*)$ /$1` (redirects all /blog/ pages to root).</li>
    <li>Manually updated high‑priority internal links (navigation, sidebar, popular posts) to new URLs.</li>
    <li>Used Screaming Frog to find and update any remaining internal broken links.</li>
    <li>Contacted top 30 linking sites and asked them to update their links (using Ahrefs broken backlinks report). 12 agreed.</li>
    <li>Added a custom 404 page with search and popular posts to retain users who still hit 404s.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Results (90 days):</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>404 errors in GSC dropped from 2,300+ to under 50.</li>
    <li>Crawl budget improved: Google crawled 340% more pages per month.</li>
    <li>Organic traffic recovered from 30% of previous level to 86% (80% recovery).</li>
    <li>Rankings for 45 keywords improved by 5‑12 positions.</li>
    <li>Inbound link equity recovered – domain authority (DA) increased from 22 to 31.</li>
    <li>Booking inquiries returned to pre‑migration levels.</li>
  </ul>
  <p><strong>Investment:</strong> ~KES 30,000 (developer time for bulk redirects + internal time). ROI: recovered in 10 days of restored bookings.</p>
  <p><strong>Key takeaway:</strong> Never change URL structures without implementing 301 redirects. The cost of fixing after the fact is much higher than doing it correctly the first time.</p>

  <h3>11. Common Broken Link Mistakes (Even After Fixing)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>❌ Using 302 (temporary) redirect instead of 301 (permanent).</strong> 302 passes less link equity. Use 301 for permanent moves.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Redirecting all 404s to the homepage.</strong> This is a poor user experience (user expects specific content, gets homepage). Redirect to the most relevant page.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Forgetting to update sitemap after adding redirects.</strong> Your XML sitemap should list only the final URLs (not the redirected ones).</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Not checking redirect chains.</strong> A → B → C → D (multiple redirects) slows down load time and dilutes link equity. Aim for direct redirects.</li>
    <li><strong>❌ Ignoring external broken links because “they don’t affect SEO”.</strong> They still affect user experience. Fix them when possible.</li>
  </ul>

