  <h3>1. What Is Thin Content? (And Why Google Penalizes It)</h3>
  <p>Thin content is any page that provides little to no value to users. Google’s <strong>Panda algorithm</strong> specifically targets thin content. Examples include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Short pages:</strong> Under 500 words with minimal information (e.g., a product page with just “Call for price”).</li>
    <li><strong>Duplicate content:</strong> Copying product descriptions from manufacturers or competitors. <a href="/duplicate-content-fix">Learn how to fix duplicate content →</a></li>
    <li><strong>Auto‑generated content:</strong> AI‑written pages with no human review or unique value.</li>
    <li><strong>Keyword‑stuffed pages:</strong> Repetitive phrases without helpful information.</li>
    <li><strong>Doorway pages:</strong> Pages created just to rank for a keyword, with no real content.</li>
    <li><strong>Affiliate thin pages:</strong> Mostly product links with little original text.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>Google’s <strong>E‑E‑A‑T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness)</strong> guidelines emphasize content created by people with real experience. For Kenyan websites, this means demonstrating local knowledge, including first‑hand examples, and updating content regularly. <a href="/eeat-seo-guide">Read our full E‑E‑A‑T guide →</a></p>

  <div style="background: #e8f5e9; padding: 20px; border-radius: 16px; margin: 25px 0;">
    <p><strong>📊 The Cost of Thin Content:</strong> A Nairobi e‑commerce store had 200 product pages with only 50‑100 words of generic description. After expanding each to 300+ unique words (with local shipping details, usage tips, and customer Q&A), organic traffic to product pages increased 340% within 90 days.</p>
  </div>

