  <h3>3. How to Audit Your Site for Thin Content (Free Tools)</h3>
  
  <h4>3.1 Screaming Frog (Word Count Crawl)</h4>
  <p>Download Screaming Frog (free up to 500 URLs). Crawl your site. Go to the “Internal” tab → “Word Count” column. Sort by lowest word count. Identify pages under 500 words – these are your thin content candidates.</p>
  
  <h4>3.2 Google Search Console (Performance + Page Inspect)</h4>
  <p>GSC → Performance → Pages. Look for pages with impressions but low clicks. These pages may be ranking (position 8‑15) but not getting clicks because the content is thin. Click on a page URL → “Inspect URL” → “View crawled page” – Google shows you what content it sees. If it’s thin, expand it.</p>
  
  <h4>3.3 Sitebulb (Free Trial)</h4>
  <p>Sitebulb offers a free trial and has a dedicated “Thin Content” audit. It flags pages with low word count, duplicate content, and low value.</p>
  
  <h4>3.4 Manual Review (For Small Sites)</h4>
  <p>Visit your key pages (homepage, services, about, blog). Ask yourself: “Does this page fully answer the user’s likely question?” If not, add more detail, examples, media, and internal links. <a href="/content-audit-services">Get a professional content audit →</a></p>

  <h3>4. How to Fix Thin Content – From 300 to 1,500+ Words</h3>
  <p>Expanding thin content is not about adding fluff. Each addition should provide genuine value. Use this checklist:</p>
  
  <h4>4.1 Add Subheadings (H2, H3) to Break Up Content</h4>
  <p>Long content needs structure. Add descriptive subheadings that answer user questions. Example for a plumber’s service page:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>H2: “Emergency Plumbing Services in Kilimani – 24/7 Availability”</li>
    <li>H3: “How Much Does Emergency Plumbing Cost in Nairobi?”</li>
    <li>H3: “What Areas Do You Serve?” (list Kilimani, Westlands, Lavington, etc.)</li>
    <li>H3: “Why Choose Us Over Other Plumbers?”</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>4.2 Answer “People Also Ask” Questions</h4>
  <p>Search Google for your target keyword. Scroll to “People also ask”. Answer each question in 40‑60 words. Add these as an FAQ section. <a href="/faq-schema-guide">Learn how to add FAQ schema for voice →</a></p>
  
  <h4>4.3 Add Real Kenyan Examples and Case Studies</h4>
  <p>Show your local expertise. Example: “Last week, we fixed a burst pipe for a family in Kilimani within 30 minutes. The repair cost KES 3,500 and saved them from water damage.” Authentic examples build trust and improve E‑E‑A‑T.</p>
  
  <h4>4.4 Include Tables, Lists, and Statistics</h4>
  <p>Google favors structured data. Use tables for pricing, lists for features, and charts for comparisons. Example: a restaurant could list “Top 5 Nyama Choma Spots in Westlands with Price Comparison”.</p>
  
  <h4>4.5 Add Images, Videos, and Infographics</h4>
  <p>Visuals increase engagement and time on page. Add before/after photos for home services, product images for e‑commerce, and tutorial videos for how‑to content. <a href="/video-seo-tips">Optimize your videos for search →</a></p>
  
  <h4>4.6 Link to Related Internal Pages (Internal Linking Strategy)</h4>
  <p>Internal links distribute authority and keep users on your site. For each expanded page, add 5‑10 internal links to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Your most important service pages (money pages).</li>
    <li>Related blog posts (e.g., from “plumbing services” to “how to prevent burst pipes”).</li>
    <li>Location pages (e.g., “Kilimani plumber” to “Westlands plumber”).</li>
    <li>Your <a href="/about">About page</a> (to build trust).</li>
    <li>Your <a href="/contact">Contact page</a> (to drive conversions).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Use descriptive anchor text (not “click here”). Example: “<a href="/emergency-plumber-kilimani">Learn more about our emergency plumber services in Kilimani</a>”. <a href="/internal-linking-guide">Read our complete internal linking guide →</a></p>
  
  <h4>4.7 Add Customer Testimonials and Reviews</h4>
  <p>Testimonials are user‑generated content that adds length and trust. Ask past customers for a 2‑3 sentence review. Add their name and location (e.g., “John, Kilimani”). <a href="/local-seo-kenya">See how local SEO uses reviews →</a></p>
  
  <h4>4.8 Include a “What to Expect” Section</h4>
  <p>For service pages, describe the process step by step. Example for an SEO agency:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Step 1: Free consultation and audit (30 minutes).</li>
    <li>Step 2: Strategy development (3 days).</li>
    <li>Step 3: Implementation (2 weeks).</li>
    <li>Step 4: Monthly reporting and adjustments.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>4.9 Add a Comparison Section (Us vs Competitors)</h4>
  <p>Create a table comparing your services to competitors. Be honest (don’t falsely claim superiority). Example:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>“Free estimate? Yes (us) vs No (competitor A) vs Yes (competitor B)”</li>
    <li>“M‑Pesa accepted? Yes, Yes, No”</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>4.10 Update Outdated Information</h4>
  <p>Old content signals irrelevance. Add a “Last updated” date. Update pricing, contact details, and examples. Google favors fresh content. <a href="/technical-seo-audit">Learn how to audit for outdated content →</a></p>

  <h3>5. Topic Clusters – Organize Content for Authority</h3>
  <p>A <strong>topic cluster</strong> is a group of interlinked pages around a core topic. It signals to Google that you are an authority on that subject. Structure:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pillar page:</strong> A comprehensive, 2,500+ word guide covering a broad topic (e.g., “Complete Guide to SEO in Kenya”).</li>
    <li><strong>Cluster content:</strong> 10‑20 related blog posts or service pages (e.g., “Keyword Research Kenya”, “Local SEO Nairobi”, “Voice Search Optimization”).</li>
    <li><strong>Internal links:</strong> Each cluster page links back to the pillar page, and the pillar page links to each cluster page.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><strong>Benefits for Kenyan websites:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li>Increases time on site (users click through to related content).</li>
    <li>Distributes link equity across your site.</li>
    <li>Helps Google understand your site’s expertise.</li>
    <li>Improves rankings for all pages in the cluster.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p>Example topic cluster for a Kenyan plumber:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Pillar page:</strong> “Complete Plumbing Services Guide – Nairobi” (2,500 words covering all services).</li>
    <li><strong>Cluster pages:</strong> “Emergency Plumber Kilimani”, “Burst Pipe Repair Cost Nairobi”, “Water Heater Installation”, “Bathroom Renovation Plumbing”, “How to Prevent Frozen Pipes in Kenya”.</li>
    <li><strong>Internal linking:</strong> Every cluster page links back to the pillar page using anchor text “Complete plumbing guide”. Pillar page links to each cluster page using descriptive anchor text.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><a href="/topic-clusters-guide">Read our full topic cluster strategy guide →</a></p>

  <h3>6. Internal Linking – The Most Overlooked Content Tool</h3>
  <p>Internal links are links from one page on your site to another. They are <strong>free ranking power</strong> that many Kenyan websites ignore. Benefits:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Distribute PageRank (link equity)</strong> from high‑authority pages (like your homepage) to deeper pages.</li>
    <li><strong>Help Google discover</strong> new pages faster.</li>
    <li><strong>Improve user engagement</strong> – users click related links and stay longer.</li>
    <li><strong>Provide context</strong> – Google understands relationships between pages.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>6.1 Internal Linking Best Practices</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use descriptive anchor text:</strong> “<a href="/emergency-plumber-kilimani">emergency plumber in Kilimani</a>” not “click here”.</li>
    <li><strong>Link from high‑authority pages</strong> (homepage, pillar content) to your money pages (services, products).</li>
    <li><strong>Aim for 3‑5 internal links per page</strong> (excluding navigation).</li>
    <li><strong>Link to pages that are 1‑2 clicks away</strong> – deep linking to older content helps it get re‑crawled.</li>
    <li><strong>Use a logical site structure</strong> – categories → subcategories → posts. Example: `/services/` → `/services/plumbing/` → `/services/plumbing/emergency`.</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid orphan pages</strong> – pages with no internal links. Google may never find them.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <h4>6.2 How to Find Internal Linking Opportunities (Free)</h4>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Screaming Frog:</strong> Crawl your site. Go to “Internal” tab → “Inlinks” column. Pages with zero inlinks are orphaned – add links to them.</li>
    <li><strong>Google Search Console:</strong> “Pages” report → “Linking pages” shows which pages have internal links and which don’t.</li>
    <li><strong>Manual brainstorming:</strong> Write a list of your top 20 most important pages. From each page, check if you link to the other 19. If not, add a link where relevant.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <p><a href="/internal-linking-tools">Recommended internal linking tools →</a></p>

  <h3>7. Content Refresh Strategy – Why Old Content Needs Love</h3>
  <p>Google prefers fresh content. An old blog post from 2022 can still rank, but updating it improves its chances. Follow this schedule:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Quarterly:</strong> Review your top 10 traffic‑driving pages. Update statistics, add new examples, and check for broken links. <a href="/broken-links-guide">See how to fix broken links →</a></li>
    <li><strong>Bi‑annually:</strong> Add 200‑300 new words to your pillar pages (e.g., new section on “2026 trends”).</li>
    <li><strong>Annually:</strong> Completely rewrite outdated content (e.g., “SEO pricing 2025” → “SEO pricing 2026”).</li>
