  <h3>1. Why Backlinks Matter – Google’s PageRank Explained</h3>
  <p>Google’s original algorithm, <strong>PageRank</strong>, was built on the idea that links are votes. A link from Site A to Site B is a recommendation. The more high‑quality recommendations you have, the more authoritative your site appears. Today, backlinks remain a top 3 ranking factor alongside content and user experience.</p>
  
  <p>For Kenyan websites, backlinks from <strong>.ke domains or locally relevant sites</strong> are especially valuable. Google sees a link from <strong>Business Daily</strong> or <strong>TechMoran</strong> as stronger than a link from a generic international directory because it signals local relevance.</p>
  
  <p><strong>Key metrics you should know:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Domain Authority (DA):</strong> A score from 1-100 predicting ranking ability. Most Kenyan small business sites have DA 10-20. Top competitors have DA 30-50.</li>
    <li><strong>Referring domains:</strong> The number of unique websites linking to you. 50-100 quality referring domains is a good target for a Kenyan business.</li>
    <li><strong>Link quality vs quantity:</strong> One link from a major Kenyan news site is worth 100 links from spammy directories.</li>
  </ul>
  
  <div style="background: #e8f5e9; padding: 20px; border-radius: 16px; margin: 25px 0;">
    <p><strong>📊 Backlink Impact Data:</strong> A Nairobi law firm went from 0 to 35 quality backlinks in 6 months (through guest posts and directory listings). Their domain authority increased from 8 to 29. Rankings for “divorce lawyer Nairobi” moved from page 3 to page 1. Organic leads tripled.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>2. Common Backlink Mistakes (Kenyan Websites)</h3>
  
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mistake 7A: No backlink strategy at all.</strong> Many Kenyan sites rely only on content, never actively building links. This is the most common mistake.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 7B: Buying cheap backlinks (Fiverr, SEO “gurus”).</strong> Paid links from low‑quality sites (PBNs, link farms) can get you a Google penalty. <a href="/google-penalty-recovery">Learn how to recover from penalties →</a></li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 7C: Ignoring local Kenyan directories.</strong> International directories (Yelp, Yellow Pages) help, but local .ke directories are undervalued.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 7D: Not using anchor text variation.</strong> Over‑optimizing anchor text (e.g., “best plumber Nairobi” on every link) looks unnatural to Google.</li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 7E: No link reclamation.</strong> When someone mentions your business but doesn’t link, you miss an opportunity. <a href="/link-reclamation-guide">Learn link reclamation →</a></li>
    <li><strong>Mistake 7F: Ignoring internal links as a complement.</strong> Internal links (covered in Section 9) distribute authority. A strong internal linking strategy makes external backlinks more effective. <a href="/internal-linking-strategy">Internal linking best practices →</a></li>
  </ul>

